                    1. Get a Comfy Bed for Your Dog
                </h2>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40]  text-sm md:text-base text-justify">Your dog
                    needs a nice, cozy place to sleep and relax. Some dogs like to curl up, while others prefer
                    stretching out. Ask the person you got the dog from about their sleeping style, or get a bed that
                    works for both.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">Pick a
                    bed that's comfy, just the right size, easy to clean, and made from dog-friendly stuff. It should be
                    big enough for them to turn around comfortably.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">Put the
                    bed in a clean, dry spot without any drafts. With time, you'll figure out if your dog likes being in
                    the middle of everything or if they prefer a quieter spot.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">
                    If your dog is used to being in a crate, the same rules apply. Don't use a crate if they're not used
                    to it. Talk to your vet or a specialist who knows about dog behavior first.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center items-center wow animate__animated animate__slideInRight">
                <img src="assets/1_dog_welfare.jpg" alt=""
                    class="w-[220px] md:w-[358px] mb-7 md:mb-0 rounded-3xl shadow-2xl shadow-black">
