            class="bg-[#fbf8f7] flex flex-col-reverse space-y-8 md:space-y-0 md:flex-row-reverse justify-center items-center py-0 md:py-14 px-2 md:px-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col align-middle w-[80%] md:w-[50%] text-justify">
                <h2
                    class="hidden md:block text-xl md:text-2xl font-bold text-[#3f3f40] mx-8 text-center wow animate__animated animate__zoomIn mb-3 md:mb-4">
                    4. Consider Company for Your Dog
                </h2>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">It's your job to make sure
                    your dog has good company, whether it's from people, other dogs, or both. Some dogs like being
                    around others more than some, but no dog enjoys being alone for a really long time.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">Before your dog comes home,
                    think about the times they'll be by themselves. Depending on what your dog likes, you might want to
                    check out a doggy day care, a trusted dog walker, or a pet sitter.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">If you find out from the
                    person you got the dog from that they get really upset when left alone (called separation anxiety),
                    talk to your vet or a behavior expert.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-3 font-normal text-[#3f3f40] text-sm md:text-base text-justify">And remember: if your dog
                    is going to be alone a lot, it might not be the best idea to bring them home.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="mr-0 md:mr-16 wow animate__animated animate__slideInLeft"> <img src="assets/4_dog_welfare.png"
